    <!-- Page Title, Problem Description, and Symptoms -->
    <div class="row">
      <div class="col-md-8 col-xl-6 text-center mx-auto">
        <!-- Title in one line -->
        <h1 class="display-4 fw-bold mb-4" style="line-height: 1.2; color: #260d5e;">
          Emergency Steps for a Pregnant Woman in Labor While Waiting for Help
        </h1>
        <!-- Brief problem description -->
        <p class="lead text-muted">
          Labor emergencies can be critical. Prompt and calm action can help safeguard both mother and baby.
        </p>
        <!-- Short symptoms section in red -->
        <p class="fs-5" style="color: red;">
          <strong>Symptoms:</strong> Severe abdominal pain, heavy bleeding, and signs of shock.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
    
    <!-- Main Content: Do's and What Not To Do -->
    <div class="row align-items-center">
      <!-- Left Column: Guidelines -->
      <div class="col-md-6">
        <h3 class="fw-bold mb-3">Immediate Steps (Do's):</h3>
        <ol class="fs-5">
          <li><strong>Call Emergency Services:</strong> Dial your local emergency number immediately.</li>
          <li><strong>Keep Her Calm:</strong> Reassure her and help her remain as comfortable as possible.</li>
          <li><strong>Monitor Vital Signs:</strong> Observe her breathing and level of consciousness closely.</li>
          <li><strong>Help Her Find a Comfortable Position:</strong> Assist her into a position that eases labor pain.</li>
          <li><strong>Stay With Her:</strong> Remain by her side until professional help arrives.</li>
        </ol>
        <h3 class="fw-bold mt-4 mb-3">What Not To Do:</h3>
        <ul class="fs-5">
          <li>Do not delay calling for emergency help.</li>
          <li>Avoid administering medications without proper medical guidance.</li>
          <li>Do not force her to change positions abruptly.</li>
          <li>Do not leave her unattended.</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="text-muted mt-3">
          <em>Note:</em> This guide is for emergency use only and does not replace professional medical care.
        </p>
      </div>
      
